      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, and I’m glad you’re seeing the big picture—thinking of the POA as a “protector” for your dad’s assets is a great way to frame it. A power of attorney is indeed a legal tool that lets you act on his behalf, and when it’s durable, it’s like a shield that stays in place even if his health changes.\n\n**How to set it up securely**\n\n1. **Start with a clear, written document**  \n   - The POA must be in writing and signed by both your dad and you.  \n   - It should specify the scope (e.g., bank accounts, investments, tax filings) and the duration (since it’s durable, it will last until he dies or the document is revoked).  \n   - Make sure the language is precise: “I, [Dad’s name], appoint [Your Name] as my durable power of attorney, authorizing them to act on my behalf for all financial matters…”\n\n2. **Notarization**  \n   - Most states require the POA to be notarized. This is a simple step that adds legal weight.  \n   - Find a notary public who can witness the signature and stamp the document.",
